OL,3,CDoomed satellite ERS-2 to crash back
OL,4,Cto Earth - but where will it land?
OL,6,FAn uncontrolled is seen tumbling
OL,7,Ftowards Earth in newly released images
OL,8,Fas it prepares to reenter the
OL,9,Fatmosphere.
OL,11,FERS-2 was launched almost 30 years ago
OL,12,Fand is expected to break up into
OL,13,Fpieces upon reentry into the the
OL,14,FEarth's atmosphere.
OL,16,FExperts from the European Space Agency
OL,17,Fsaid the ERS-2 will break up into
OL,18,Ffragments around 80 km above the
OL,19,FEarth's surface and the vast majority
OL,20,Fof these will burn up in the
OL,21,Fatmosphere.
