OL,3,CDoomed satellite ERS-2 to crash back
OL,4,Cto Earth - but where will it land?
OL,6,FESA's Space Debris Office is
OL,7,Ffrequently updating its prediction for
OL,8,Fwhere and when ERS-2 will reenter the
OL,9,Fatmosphere and begin to burn up.
OL,11,FThe ESA said: "Some fragments could
OL,12,Freach Earth's surface, where they will
OL,13,Fmost likely fall into the ocean. None
OL,14,Fof these fragments will contain any
OL,15,Ftoxic or radioactive substances."
OL,17,FWhat is the risk of being hit by
OL,18,Ffalling debris?
